<DOC><DOCNO> AP880807-0032 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 1619EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-Survivors     08-07 0237</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Survivors,0250</SECOND><HEAD>More Than 300 Found Alive After Floods</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rescuers have found 311 people who were missingand presumed dead after flash floods and heavy rains ravaged aprovince on the Chinese coast, a newspaper reported.   A total of 264 people were confirmed dead and 50 were stillmissing from floods that hit Zhejiang province July 29-30, theXinmin Evening News said Saturday.   It did not say how or where the 311 survivors were found.   The floods came after about 18 inches of rain fell within sixhours in parts of five counties near Ningbo, a city on the EastChina Sea, according to Qiu Weikang, a Ningbo city official.   The Evening News said the rains and flooding destroyed 27,000houses and 944 schools. More than 52,000 people were moved totemporary shelters.   The report said 40 million acres were flooded.   The economic loss was estimated at more than $162 million, thepaper said, and residents say it was the worst rainfall in the areain 100 years.   On Saturday, floods inundated Fenyang county in northern Shanxiprovince. The official Xinhua News Agency reported that at least 21people died and 19 were missing after rain fell for more than threehours.   More than 800 people have died in floods this year in coastal,southern and northern China. Another 500 were killed by a heat wavein cities in the Yangtze River valley.</TEXT></DOC>